ate how "green media archaeology" can make sound studies vibrate at an ecological frequency while opening the ears of eco-criticism. Throughout this eye-opening and timely book he makes readers more aware of the costs and consequences of their personal media consumption by prompting comparisons with non-digital, non-electronic technologies and by offering different ways in which sound media can become eco-sonic media. In the process, he forges interdisciplinary connections, opens new avenues of research, and poses fresh theoretical questions for scholars and students of media, sound studies, and contemporary environmental history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAudio equipment industryxEnvironmental aspects. 0aSound in mass mediaxHistory. 0aSound recordingsxEnvironmental aspects. 0aSoundxRecording and reproducingxEquipment and suppliesxEnvironmental aspects. 0aSoundxRecording and reproducingxEquipment and suppliesxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh  aaudio equipment history.  aaudio recording history.  acontemporary environmental history.  acontemporary mediascape.  adivining rods.  adomestic music machines.  aearly sound technology.  aeco sonic media.  aecological critique.  agramophones.  agreen media archaeology.  agreen media.  agreening the media.  ahistory of sound media.  amedia artifacts.  amedia culture.  anondigital sound technology.  apersonal media.  apre electronic media.  asound media technologies.  asound recording equipment.  asound recordings.  asound studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052028613940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096149440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520961494423Coveruhttps://www.degru